	% title n
	line 1
	line 2...
	line n	
		Writes lines centered on the screen using the current
		font and font color.

	% sleep s
		sleep for s number of seconds.

	% clear
		Clears the graphics image to black.

	% zoom mag
		Where mag is the magnification factor.

	% offset x y
		When an image doesn't fit in the window, offset can be 
		used to translate the image around in the window.
	
	% display [# z value]
		Draws the z section to the center of the screen.  Uses
		the current offset and zoom.

	% movie [# of repeats]
		Plays an animation of the image stack forwand and then
		looping backwards for the number of repeats set.

	% moviedelay [# frames]	
		Slows the movie down by waiting the given number of
		frames.
	

	The following fuctions are used for subwindows.

	% windraw x1 y1 x2 y2
		Draws the current image data to a box with lower left
		corner (x1, y1) and upper right corner (x2, y2).
		The drawing won't be displayed until winshow is called.
		This allows one to draw multipule subwindows.

	% section z
		Selects the current z value that will be drawn with 
		windraw.

	% winshow
		Allows one to see the all subwindow drawing.
	
	% winclear
		Clears the subwindow buffer.


	Functions that use overlay planes.

	% textxy x y
		Sets the position (x, y) where the text will be drawn.

	% print "string"
		Prints the string at the current (x, y) position, with
		the current font.

	% charcode c
		Prints a character to the screen.  Useful for drawing
		extended characters to the screen.

	% text x y
	string
		writes the string at (x, y) to the overlay planes.
				
	% line x1 y1 x2 y2
		draws a line from (x1,y1) to (x2, y2) in the current
		text color to the overlay planes

	% oversetcolor index
		Select the current overlay color. (0 = transparent)

	% overcolor red green blue 
		select the red, green and blue values of the overlay
		text.  Red, green and blue are integers between 0-255.
	
	% overclear
		clears the overlay planes used for writing text.

	% label string
		draws string to last windraw coords.

	% labelxy x y
		Set offset to label string draw by adding x and y.

	% labelcorner ll, lr, ur, ul
		Set corner of window to put label in. (ll = lower-left,
		lr = lower-right, ur = upper-right, ul = upper-left)

	Exit mrcv by using one of the commands.
	
	% quit
		Quits the mrcv program.  If this command isn't at the 
		end of the script file mrcv will go into interactive 
		mode at the end of the script.
		
	% keywait 
		Waits for a keyboard input.

	% keyquit 
		Waits for keyboard input before quitting.


